<TEI.2><text><body><div1 type="alphabetic letter" n="B" org="uniform" sample="complete"><entryFree key="Britain" type="main" opt="n"><orth extent="full" opt="n">Britain,</orth> the country of the English: <bibl n="shak. lll 4.1.126" default="NO" valid="yes">LLL IV, 1, 126</bibl>. <cit><quote>--'s isle</quote> <bibl n="shak. 2h6 1.3.47" default="NO" valid="yes">H6B I, 3, 47</bibl></cit>. <bibl n="shak. h8 1.1.21" default="NO" valid="yes">H8 I, 1, 21</bibl>. <bibl n="shak. cym 1.4.1" default="NO" valid="yes">Cymb. I, 4, 1</bibl>. <bibl n="shak. cym 1.4.1" default="NO" valid="yes">Cymb. I, 4, 1</bibl> <bibl n="shak. cym 1.6.113" default="NO" valid="yes">I, 6, 113</bibl>. <bibl n="shak. cym 2.4.19" default="NO" valid="yes">II, 4, 19</bibl>. <bibl n="shak. cym 2.4.19" default="NO" valid="yes">II, 4, 19</bibl> <bibl n="shak. cym 5.1.20" default="NO" valid="yes">V, 1, 20</bibl> etc. <cit><quote>in the B. court,</quote> <bibl n="shak. cym 2.4.37" default="NO" valid="yes">Cymb. II, 4, 37</bibl></cit> (cf. <emph>on Lethe warf, Tiber banks, Rome gates, Afric sun</emph>). Ancient orthography makes no distinction between <emph>Britain, Bretagne</emph> and <emph>Briton,</emph> q. v.
</entryFree></div1></body></text></TEI.2>